{"type":"text","timestamp":1781081417748,"sessionID":"ses_14f476edcffe1MiVLPNn4U9ix4","part":{"id":"prt_eb0b981d2001szEYzvTX3QbzyW","messageID":"msg_eb0b97818001en22DLeImF1tka","sessionID":"ses_14f476edcffe1MiVLPNn4U9ix4","type":"text","text":"Now I have everything I need. Let me write the analysis.\n\n**Reward analysis:**\n- Single tier (tier9_performance) with 5 binary test cases (no-flags, -1, -l, -S, -C) on a 10k-entry directory\n- Each case scored 1 if `diff` byte-exact-match vs GNU ls (after trailing whitespace normalization), else 0\n- 60s per-case timeout — slow/incorrect/crashed → 0 for that case\n- Score = pass_rate of tier9 × 1.0 (weighted sum, but only one tier)\n- Cheating gates: reward file manipulation, banned execve (ls/dir/vdir/oracle), oracle bypass, identical-binary hash check, banned crates, etc.\n- Failure path emits valid `{\"score\":0, \"subscores\":[], \"additional_data\":{...}}`\n- compute_reward.py is standalone — no agent imports\n- Baseline (no Cargo.toml or build failure) → fail_with \"not_a_rust_project\" / \"rust_build_failed\" → 0.0\n\n**Dimensions:** Each test case is a different flag mode. The 5 modes test different things (correctness across flag surface + perf under 60s). No mean-of-dim gaming risk — each is binary exact match. No \"easy dimension\" — all require correct output. The `-l` case is hardest (needs stat per entry) but not unreasonably so.\n\n**Shortcut/trivial:** Empty output, constants, copying ls — blocked by exact diff vs oracle + hash-equality check + banned execve + banned crates. No partial credit for \"almost matches.\"","time":{"start":1781081407954,"end":1781081417739}}}
